      <hedline>
        <hl1>Muscle Power</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Piotr Graff letter on Aug 3 article about human-powered devices recalls owning handheld dynamo-operated flashlight in 1945 in Poland (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Power From the People Breaks the Hold of Batteries and Plugs,'' (Aug. 3), about human-powered devices: I remember owning a handheld, dynamo-operated flashlight in 1945 in Poland. It was palm-size and cone-shaped, with a hand-squeezed pedal attached to the narrow side. It didn't accumulate energy -- you had to squeeze it hard all the time, and it gave just enough light for you not to break a leg while walking after dark through the rubble in the streets of Warsaw.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Power From the People Breaks the Hold of Batteries and Plugs,'' (Aug. 3), about human-powered devices: I remember owning a handheld, dynamo-operated flashlight in 1945 in Poland. It was palm-size and cone-shaped, with a hand-squeezed pedal attached to the narrow side. It didn't accumulate energy -- you had to squeeze it hard all the time, and it gave just enough light for you not to break a leg while walking after dark through the rubble in the streets of Warsaw.</p>
        <p>This is an old idea whose time may have finally come.</p>
        <p>PIOTR GRAFF  Guilford, Vt.</p>
      </block>
